August was the last full month of Ethereum mining. Between Sept. 10 and 20, the blockchain will shift as part of <a href="https://www.theblock.co/post/166708/the-merge-everything-you-need-to-know-about-ethereums-big-upgrade" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-v-f87c67ca="">The Merge</a> from a proof-of-work (PoW) mechanism for block creation to a proof-of-stake (PoS) system, after which PoW mining on Ethereum will no longer take place. Some in the industry have speculated that PoW forks of Ethereum may emerge post-Merge, providing a new source of income for miners. Whether those forks will succeed is unknown.<br data-v-f87c67ca="">
<br data-v-f87c67ca="">
With proof-of-work, miners generate hashes in a competitive effort to match the hash of the current target block. By contrast, Ethereum's proof-of-stake system involves an array of validators that commit their funds.&nbsp;
